Introduction

This analysis uses publicly available data from Universal Bank in an attempt to predict whether a customer will accept a personal loan offer extended by the bank.

library(dplyr)

Distributions

It seems strange that there are negative values for experience we will take a closer look by plotting the distribution. The experience variable has a max of 43 and appears continuous rather than catagorical, we may want to consider dropping these negative observations. Education has 3 levels and is a catagorical variable in this dataset.

maxs = sapply(loans, max)
binary_feats = loans[which(maxs == 1)]
cont_feats = loans[which(maxs != 1)]

binary.dta = gather(binary_feats) # Transforming the data into long format for plotting
cont.dta = gather(cont_feats)

ggplot(binary.dta, aes(value)) +

Since experience and age are highly correlated it may help our model performance if we remove one of these variables. I removed the experience variable instead of age because of the ambiguous negative values in experience.

loans = loans[,-2];

Boxplot

Clearly there is a large difference in loan acceptance between income groups. High income alone did not guarantee loan acceptance however people making below ~100K/year almost never accept the offer.

ggplot(loans, aes(Income, factor(Personal.Loan), fill=factor(Personal.Loan))) +
  geom_boxplot() +
  coord_flip() +
  theme(legend.position="none") +
  scale_y_discrete(name='Loan Status', labels=c("Not Accepted", "Accepted")) +
  scale_x_continuous(name='Income', breaks=seq(0,200,by=50),labels=paste(seq(0,200, 50), 'K', sep=''))+
  labs(title = "Income vs. Loan Status");

Classification Models

Data Preparation

Earlier we noticed that education appears to be a catagorical variable in this dataset, here we will create a model matrix with dummies for the levels of education.

dta.temp = loans
dta.temp$Education = factor(dta.temp$Education)   
feats.temp = model.matrix(Personal.Loan~.,data=dta.temp)[,-1]
resp.temp = loans$Personal.Loan

one_hot = data.frame(feats.temp, 'Personal.Loan'=resp.temp);

Here we use min max scaling to normalize the dataset, later we will want to have this on hand.

maxs <- apply(one_hot[,], 2, max)
mins <- apply(one_hot[,], 2, min);

  scaled.data <- as.data.frame(scale(one_hot[,],center = mins, scale = maxs - mins));

Logistic Regression

set.seed(1)
temp.loans = one_hot
temp.loans$Personal.Loan = ifelse(temp.loans$Personal.Loan==1, 'Accepted', 'Not Accepted');

  glm.fit = glm(factor(Personal.Loan)~., data=temp.loans[train,], family='binomial') # Fitting on the training set

  glm.probs = predict(glm.fit, temp.loans[test,], type='response') # Predicting on the test set
  contrasts(factor(temp.loans$Personal.Loan));
##              Not Accepted
## Accepted                0
## Not Accepted            1

ROC: Logistic Regression

pred = prediction(glm.probs, factor(temp.loans[test,12]))
perf = performance(pred,"tpr", "fpr")
{plot(perf, colorize= T, lwd=3)
abline(a=0,b=1, col='grey', lty=2)};

  auc_ROCR = performance(pred, "auc")
  auc_ROCR = auc_ROCR@y.values[[1]]
  auc_ROCR;
## [1] 0.9583469
  cuts = performance(pred,'acc') # returns an object full of performance metrics
  cutoffs = cuts@x.values[[1]]
  accuracy = cuts@y.values[[1]];
  
  which(accuracy==max(accuracy)) # find the cutoff that produces the best accuracy
## [1] 904 910 918 940
  cutoffs[904];
##      3569 
## 0.6280955

Confusion Matrix: Logistic Regression

We are able to achieve a high auc of .958 but from the confusion matrix we can see that we have classified quite a few observations who accepted their loan offer as ‘not accepted’. Since the goal is to increase the number of accepted loans and making an offer has little cost associated for the bank we would rather have a few more false positives than false negatives, we should keep this in mind moving forward.

pred.glm = ifelse(glm.probs > 0.6280955, 'Not Accepted','Accepted') #assing labels to the probabilities based on the threshold that maximizes accuracy

  table(pred.glm, temp.loans[test,12]) # Confusion Matrix
##               
## pred.glm       Accepted Not Accepted
##   Accepted           78           19
##   Not Accepted       29          874
  1-mean(pred.glm!=temp.loans[test,12]); # Accuracy
## [1] 0.952

Random Forest

Grid Search: Random Forest

Instead of setting mtry=sqrt(p) we will use a grid search to determine the optimal value. It looks like setting mtry=5 could produce a pretty good result without having to consider an overwhelming number of features.

set.seed(1)

control = trainControl(method="cv", number=5, search="grid")
tunegrid = expand.grid(.mtry=c(1:11))
rf_gridsearch = caret::train(factor(Personal.Loan)~., 
                       data=temp.loans[train,], 
                       method="rf", 
                       metric="Accuracy", 
                       tuneGrid=tunegrid, 
                       trControl=control,
                       ntree=50);

print(rf_gridsearch)

Fitting the Final Model: Random Forest

After trying some different values for the number of trees to grow it appears that setting ntrees=~15 will yield the best results.

set.seed(1)
control = trainControl(method="none")
tunegrid = expand.grid(.mtry=5)
rf_final = caret::train(factor(Personal.Loan)~., 
                       data=temp.loans[train,], 
                       method="rf", 
                       metric="Accuracy", 
                       tuneGrid=tunegrid, 
                       trControl=control,
                       importance=TRUE,
                       ntree=15);

varImp(rf_final)

pred.rf = predict(rf_final, temp.loans[test,], type='prob', n.trees=15);

x.train = temp.loans[train,-12]

K-Nearest Neighbors

Here we use the normalized data with min max scaling to improve performance, since KNN is calculating the distance between observations we want everything on the same scale.

scaled.data$Personal.Loan = ifelse(scaled.data$Personal.Loan==1, 'Accepted', 'Not Accepted');
  scale.train.x = scaled.data[train, -12]
  scale.train.y = scaled.data[train,12];

  scale.test.x = scaled.data[test, -12]
  scale.test.y = scaled.data[test, 12];

Choosing K

Here the best auc was achieved using K=54, however this is hardly any better than using the more flexible model with k=35, we will procede with k=35.

test_errors = NULL
test_auc = NULL

set.seed(1)
for(i in seq(1,75, by=1)){
  knn.pred= knn(scale.train.x, scale.test.x, factor(scale.train.y), k=i, prob=T)
  table(knn.pred, scale.test.y)
  knn.probs = attr(knn.pred, "prob")
  pred = prediction(knn.probs, factor(scale.test.y))
  perf = performance(pred,"tpr", "fpr")
  auc_ROCR = performance(pred, "auc") # returns the auc
  auc_ROCR = auc_ROCR@y.values[[1]]
  auc_ROCR
  test_errors = c(test_errors, mean(knn.pred!=scale.test.y)) # get accuracy scores
  test_auc = c(test_auc, auc_ROCR) # get auc scores 
}
  
  head(test_errors)
## [1] 0.039 0.043 0.038 0.040 0.045 0.045
  head(test_auc);
## [1] 0.5000000 0.5641281 0.6321755 0.6831064 0.7301232 0.7827705
  which(test_auc==max(test_auc));
## [1] 54
  plot(1:75, test_auc, col='blue');

Fitting the Best Model: NN

The best model ended up using a single layer with 10 hidden nodes.

set.seed(1)
mlp_grid = expand.grid(layer1 = 10,
                       layer2 = 0,
                       layer3 = 0);

fitControl = trainControl(method='none')

mlp_fit.final = caret::train(x = scale.train.x,
                y = factor(scale.train.y),
                method='mlpML',
                trControl= fitControl,
                linout= F,
                tuneGrid = mlp_grid);


nn.probs = predict(mlp_fit.final, scale.test.x, type='prob');

Confusion Matrix: NN

Here we can see that the neural network is able to give us a model with an extremely low false positive rate, if we were to use this model we could be confident that people who are predicted to accept the loan offer will actually accept. Compared to the other boosted model we have a few more false negatives, if our goal is to maximize the total number of loans accepted we could use another model or just send offers to everyone but this neural network provides a good balance of both precision and recall.

yhat.nn = ifelse(nn.probs[,2] > 0.8214471, 'Accepted', 'Not Accepted')
